<title type="html"><![CDATA[Contra, Kontora, Probotector, Gryzor]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=1150&amp;p=9994#p9994"><![CDATA[
This is called "ateji" (当て字) and is basically a form of rebus used with kanji. The practice started from the view that it was necessary to have kanji equivalents of foreign loadwords (<!-- m --><a class="postlink" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Japanese_words_of_Portuguese_origin">http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Japanese_w ... ese_origin</a><!-- m -->)<br /><br />I guess its used for the same reason you would say "effervescent" instead of "fizzy", a bunch of 80-stroke kanji that haven't been used since the US was a British colony is more impressive than plain old katakana. It's also fun to apply to your name and sign your Japanese 9 homework with it.<br /><br />P.S. Suprising that no one mentioned <em>Salamander</em>.<br /><br />P.P.S. For the record, <em>Gryzor</em> was the name of the Speccy/C64 ports of the game by Ocean.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=311">zx-1</a> — Tue Feb 21, 2006 3:17 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
